<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="260" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,747,657,684]" box="[151,747,657,684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,747,657,684]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Cabrera &amp; Segarra, 2008" authorityName="Cabrera &amp; Segarra" authorityYear="2008" box="[151,747,657,684]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabebuia">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,747,657,684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,422,657,684]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Holopothrips tabebuia</emphasis>
Cabrera &amp; Segarra, 2008
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,729,971]" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">
This species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[523,657,729,755]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
breeding inside distorted leaves of 
<emphasis box="[1057,1308,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Tabebuia heterophylla</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bignoniaceae</taxonomicName>
). It is widespread in the Caribbean region and also reported to Florida. This thrips induce huge gall-like deformations on 
<emphasis box="[283,386,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Tabebuia</emphasis>
leaves, which become wrinkled and curled with a very hard epidermis. It was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,286,837,863]" name="Guadeloupe" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Guadeloupe</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[342,466,837,863]" name="Martinique" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Martinique</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, B. &amp; Etienne, J. &amp; Ovarbury, T." box="[510,738,837,863]" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" pagination="419 - 420" refId="ref4802" refString="Michel, B., Etienne, J. &amp; Ovarbury, T. (2008) A new invasive thrips in the French Antilles: Holopothrips tabebuia (Thys., Phlaeothripidae). Bulletin de la Societe entomologique de France, 113, 419 - 420." type="journal article" year="2008">
Michel 
<emphasis box="[597,646,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">et al</emphasis>
. (2008)
</bibRefCitation>
, and can be found in almost all the small surrounding islands, Marie-Galante, the Saintes archipelago, Les îles du nord, Saint Bartélémy, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1029,1173,873,899]" name="Sint Martin" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Saint Martin</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabrera &amp; Segarra" authorityYear="2008" box="[1183,1436,873,899]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabebuia">
<emphasis box="[1183,1436,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">Holopothrips tabebuia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sharply bicoloured body, distinguishable from the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bournier" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[758,904,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquilinus">
<emphasis box="[758,904,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="260">H. inquilinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the uniformly brown head, and the presence of only one pair of epimeral setae on pronotum.
</paragraph>
